text: Ok here is my thoughts and yes, my opinion is going to be semi biased since this book is in my top ten favorite books of all time. That being  said if you have not already read the book please then maybe then maybe my review may make more sense as shall the trailer. First may I say seeing Harrison Ford play John Thornton seems like a role he was made to play, one of three I can say and I am sure anyone can guess the other two roles. That being said, let's first talk about the book first then the trailer. John Thornton is not really a huge part of the book as a whole, but yet at the same time is. John arrives in the book fairly late however the bond between him and Buck is unmatched and so beautifully written. Now I will not go too much further into this as not to wanting to spoil it for those who have not read the book (If that is possible). Now let's discuss the narrative of the book, it is some of the best story telling I have ever seen. It comes close to another one of my top ten favorite books which is the Old Man and the Sea. Great book. I digress, this trailer holds up. Yes looks like they took some creative liberty but still remained true to the source material. Now everyone wants to pick apart the CGI dog. Ok let's think about this for a second. In the book the emotions expressions and animation they give Buck I don't think they could touch on with a trained dog. Also I don't think it looks terrible. So that is my thoughts.

text: I really don't like the CGI here, not because it isn't done well. But if you read the book it's really out of place. Buck seems too fluid and cartoony in this movie; and the trailer seems light hearted. Compared to the book, where it has a more mature and serious theme/setting. As it seems in the movie, it will show Buck and Harrison Ford's journey together; where as in the book, it's a telling of Buck just trying to survive in the world with danger lurking on every corner. The book is very violent, and harsh to all characters. Whether it be the main, side, good, or evil. No one is protected by the plot, but are rather held at the mercy of their environment. It's a pretty grounded setup. For the CGI, I think they just could've have a real dog act where the scenes are quite and calm, and then switch to animation when there is action, similar to lady and the tramp remake. But still have its animation be stiff, lacking in emotional facial expressions for grounded reality. This movie will probably be at least ok, and I at least hope that this will get people interested in the book.

text: I am a little bit skeptical, but I am willing to give the movie a chance if it's even slightly better than an earlier live action "adaptation" attempt that barely even had Buck in it.  To be fair though, this story would be difficult to have a faithful adaptation without it being completely animated given the amount of violence involving dogs. R rated animations are probably harder to sell people on, and some parent would probably overlook that rating and assume that it's for kids because it's animated and its protagonist is a dog. Look at Plague dogs, for example. Definitely not a kid friendly film, but a lot of people claim to have seen it as children under the impression it was a kids film.

text: In earlier days, everyone on youtube used to fight. Now every comment is exactly the same, with everyone copying eachother.  Yes, the animals are CGI. This is probably because while making a film about the wild, they didn't want to mistreat the wild. Animals, even dogs, have repeatedly been mistreated on filmsets. So maybe this is their way to respect the wild and maybe that's why Harrison Ford agreed. I know the CGI seems annoying but maybe we should watch the movie and then judge wether it's good or bad?  Once upon a time, people had their own individual opinions. Irl it's still this way, but on the internet this weird cult like group thinking has developed.  EDIT: Watched the movie today and it was very heartwarming. It has a very high audience score on RT so the people who saw it seem to like it. Anyway it also became very clear why they used CGI dogs.
